\c 107
\cl Psalm 107
\s1 Paratum cor meus.
\cd The prophet praiseth God for benefits received.
\p
\v 1 A canticle of a psalm for David himself.
\p
\v 2 My heart is ready, O God, my heart is ready: I will sing, and will give praise, with my glory.
\p
\v 3 Arise, my glory; arise, psaltery and harp: I will arise in the morning early.
\p
\v 4 I will praise thee, O Lord, among the people: and I will sing unto thee among the nations.
\p
\v 5 For thy mercy is great above the heavens: and thy truth even unto the clouds.
\p
\v 6 Be thou exalted, O God, above the heavens, and thy glory over all the earth: 7 that thy beloved may be delivered.
\p Save with thy right hand and hear me. 8 God hath spoken in his holiness:
\p I will rejoice, and I will divide Sichem: and I will mete out the vale of tabernacles.
\p
\v 9 Galaad is mine, and Manasses is mine: and Ephraim the protection of my head.
\p Juda is my king: 10 Moab the pot of my hope.
\p Over Edom I will stretch out my shoe: the aliens are become my friends.
\p
\v 11 Who will bring me into the strong city? who will lead me into Edom?
\p
\v 12 Wilt not thou, O God, who hast cast us off? and wilt not thou, O God, go forth with our armies?
\p
\v 13 O grant us help from trouble: for vain is the help of man.
\p
\v 14 Through God we shall do mightily: and he will bring our enemies to nothing.
\f + \fr 107:1\ft Himself. By repeating here what occurs in Psalm lvi., and lix. David teaches us to excite our fervour by such sentiments as have formerly made an impression upon us. (Berthier) --- He spoke before of his own victories: now he considers those of Christ, and of his Church, (Genebrard) as well as the state of the captives. (Theodoret) (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 107:2\ft My heart, etc. Is not repeated in Hebrew. But it is, [in] Psalm 56:8.\f*
\f + \fr 107:3\ft Arise, my glory. Is found also in this psalm, though not here in Hebrew, etc. St. Jerome (ad Sun.) thinks some copyist has inserted it. (Calmet) --- But it seems to be here in its proper place. (Berthier)\f*
\f + \fr 107:4\ft Nations. David made various conquests, which prefigured those of Christ, to whom the rest of the psalm belongs. (St. Augustine) (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 107:7\ft That. See Psalm 59:7. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 107:8\ft Holiness. Or holy one, sancto: (Haydock) meaning Jeremias 25:11., who foretold the end of the captivity, (Calmet) or David himself, and the Messias, his son, in whom he will rejoice. (Haydock)\f*
